The movement to obtain [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|marriage rights]] and benefits for same-sex couples in the United States began in the 1970s,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|title=The Great Undoing?|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/06/20/great-undoing|work=[[The Advocate]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> but became more prominent in [[Politics of the United States|U.S. politics]] in 1993 when the [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] declared the state's prohibition to be unconstitutional in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Same Sex Marriage Laws - History|url=http://www.ncsl.org/issues-research/human-services/same-sex-marriage-laws.aspx|publisher=National Conference of State Legislatures|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> During the 21st century, public support for legalizing same-sex marriage has grown considerably,<ref name="columbia.edu">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~jrl2124/Lax_Phillips_Gay_Policy_Responsiveness_2009.pdf |title=Gay Rights in the States: Public Opinion and Policy Responsiveness |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Nate|title=Support for Gay Marriage Outweighs Opposition in Polls|url=http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/support-for-gay-marriage-outweighs-opposition-in-polls/|accessdate=October 28, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 9, 2012}}</ref> and various national polls conducted since 2011 show that a majority of Americans support same-sex marriage.<ref>See
