==Legal issues==
{{See also|Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States}}

===Federal law===
The legal issues surrounding same-sex marriage in the United States are complicated by the nation's [[federalism|federal]] system of government. Prior to 1996, the federal government did not define marriage; any marriage recognized by a [[U.S. state|state]] was recognized by the federal government, even if that marriage was not recognized by one or more other states (as was the case with interracial marriage before 1967 due to [[anti-miscegenation laws]]). With the passage of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] (DOMA) in 1996, a marriage was explicitly defined in federal law as a union of one man and one woman.<ref>{{usc|1|7}}.</ref>

DOMA was challenged in the [[United States federal courts|federal court system]]. On July 8, 2010, Judge [[Joseph Louis Tauro|Joseph Tauro]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District Court of Massachusetts]] held that the denial of federal rights and benefits to lawfully married Massachusetts same-sex couples is unconstitutional under the [[Tenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Tenth Amendment]] to the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]].<ref name="hrc.org">{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09marriage.html|title=Judge Topples U.S. Rejection of Gay Unions | work = [[The New York Times]] |date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=June 2, 2011|first1=Abby|last1=Goodnough|first2=John|last2=Schwartz}}</ref><ref name="politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com">{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2010/07/09/judge-rules-federal-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional/?iref=allsearch&fbid=2-HnSdp2S6g|title=Judge rules federal same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional|work=CNN|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> Since 2010, eight federal courts have found DOMA to be unconstitutional on issues including bankruptcy, public employee benefits, [[estate tax]]es, and immigration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/states/entry/c/doma|title=The Defense of Marriage Act|work=Freedom to Marry|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/31/doma-unconstitutional-ruling-appeals-court-boston_n_1559031.html|title=DOMA Ruled Unconstitutional By Federal Appeals Court  |last=Lavoie |first=Denise |date=May 31, 2012 |work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.pewstates.org/projects/stateline/headlines/defense-of-marriage-act-discriminates-against-gays-federal-court-rules-85899424320|title=Defense of Marriage Act Discriminates Against Gays, Federal Court Rules|last=Malewitz|first=Jim|date=October 18, 2012|work=Pewstates.org|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> On October 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit |U.S. 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals]] became the first court<ref>{{cite web|last=Tiven|first=Rachel|title=Edie Wins! Another Ruling Against DOMA, What It Means|url=http://www.immigrationequality.org/2012/10/edie-wins-another-ruling-against-doma-what-it-means/|publisher=[[Immigration Equality (organization)]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> to hold sexual orientation to be a [[suspect classification|quasi-suspect classification]] and applied [[intermediate scrutiny]] to strike down Section 3 of DOMA as unconstitutional in ''[[Windsor v. United States]]''.<ref>[http://www.ca2.uscourts.gov/decisions/isysquery/1afe4f62-fbf9-4e0d-a409-26ab7396971e/1/doc/12-2335_complete_opn.pdf ''Windsor v. United States''], 12-2335-cv(L), October 18, 2012.</ref> ''Windsor'' and four other federal cases are awaiting a response for review by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Geidner|first=Chris|title=BREAKING: DOJ Asks Supreme Court to Take Two DOMA Cases, Maintains Law Is Unconstitutional|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/poliglot/2012/07/breaking-doj-asks-supreme-court-to-take-two-doma-c.html|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=Metro Weekly|date=July 3, 2012}}
*{{cite news|last=Shapiro|first=Lila|title=Edie Windsor vs. DOMA: 83-Year-Old Lesbian Petitions U.S. Supreme Court To Hear Case|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/edie-windsor-doma_n_1675983.html|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=July 16, 2012}}
*Also see
